Condition-Based Monitoring: Gear Box Analysis

Phase 17: CBM Gear Box Analysis Example

This notebook demonstrates the complete workflow for condition-based monitoring of gear boxes using vibration analysis techniques. It implements the Python equivalent of the MATLAB example_CBM_Gear_Box_Analysis.m script.

Overview

This example covers:

  • Statistical feature extraction (Crest Factor, RMS, High-order moments)
  • Time-frequency analysis (CWT Scalograms, DWVD, LPC Spectrograms)
  • Nonlinearity detection using Hlder exponents
  • Damage feature extraction (NA4M, NB4M, M6A, M8A)

Background

Gear box condition monitoring relies on analyzing vibration signatures to detect:

  • Tooth wear and breakage
  • Shaft misalignment
  • Bearing deterioration
  • Lubrication issues

The analysis uses both time-domain statistical features and frequency-domain characteristics to identify damage patterns.

References

  1. Randall, R.B. (2011). Vibration-based Condition Monitoring. John Wiley & Sons.
  2. Lebold, M., et al. (2000). Review of Vibration Analysis Methods for Gearbox Diagnostics and Prognostics. Machinery Failure Prevention Technology.
  3. Antoni, J. (2006). The Spectral Kurtosis: A Useful Tool for Characterising Non-stationary Signals. Mechanical Systems and Signal Processing.

1. Data Loading and Preparation

Load the gear box vibration data from the CBM dataset. This data contains both healthy and damaged gear box measurements.

In[2]:
# Load gear box data
try:
    # Import data loading function
    from shmtools.utils import import_CBMData_shm
    
    # Check if CBM data file exists
    data_path = project_root / 'examples' / 'data' / 'data_CBM.mat'
    
    if data_path.exists():
        print(f"Loading data from: {data_path}")
        
        # Import CBM data using SHMTools function
        dataset, damageStates, stateList, fs = import_CBMData_shm()
        
        # Convert to expected format
        X = dataset  # Shape: (samples, channels, instances)
        labels = damageStates.flatten()  # Damage labels
        
        print(f"Data shape: {X.shape}")
        print(f"Sampling frequency: {fs} Hz")
        print(f"Duration per measurement: {X.shape[0]/fs:.2f} seconds")
        print(f"Number of instances: {X.shape[2]}")
        print(f"Damage states: {np.unique(labels, return_counts=True)}")
        
        # Update n_instances to match actual data
        n_instances = X.shape[2]
        
    else:
        print(f" Data file not found at {data_path}")
        print("Creating synthetic gear box data for demonstration...")
        
        # Create synthetic gear box vibration data
        fs = 25600  # 25.6 kHz sampling rate
        duration = 2.0  # 2 seconds
        n_samples = int(fs * duration)
        n_channels = 2
        n_instances = 20  # 10 healthy + 10 damaged
        
        t = np.linspace(0, duration, n_samples)
        
        # Generate synthetic data
        X = np.zeros((n_samples, n_channels, n_instances))
        
        # Gear mesh frequency (typical for gearbox)
        gear_mesh_freq = 200  # Hz
        
        for i in range(n_instances):
            for ch in range(n_channels):
                # Base gear mesh signal
                signal = np.sin(2*np.pi*gear_mesh_freq*t)
                
                # Add harmonics
                for h in range(2, 6):
                    signal += 0.5/h * np.sin(2*np.pi*h*gear_mesh_freq*t)
                
                # Add random noise
                signal += 0.1 * np.random.randn(n_samples)
                
                # Simulate damage for second half of instances
                if i >= n_instances // 2:
                    # Add impulsive damage at gear mesh rate
                    impulse_period = int(fs / gear_mesh_freq)
                    for imp_idx in range(0, n_samples, impulse_period):
                        if imp_idx < n_samples - 50:
                            # Add exponentially decaying impulse
                            impulse = np.exp(-np.arange(50) * 0.1) * np.random.exponential(2)
                            signal[imp_idx:imp_idx+50] += impulse
                
                X[:, ch, i] = signal
        
        # Create labels (0 = healthy, 1 = damaged)
        labels = np.concatenate([np.zeros(n_instances//2), np.ones(n_instances//2)])
        
        print(f" Generated synthetic data: {X.shape}")
        print(f"Healthy instances: {np.sum(labels == 0)}")
        print(f"Damaged instances: {np.sum(labels == 1)}")
        
except Exception as e:
    print(f" Error loading data: {e}")

3. Statistical Feature Extraction

Extract time-domain statistical features that are sensitive to gear damage:

  • Crest Factor: Peak-to-RMS ratio (sensitive to impulses)
  • Statistical Moments: Mean, Standard deviation, Skewness, Kurtosis
  • RMS: Root mean square energy
  • High-order moments: M6A, M8A for extreme outlier detection
In[4]:
print("Extracting statistical features...")

# Extract statistical features
try:
    # Crest Factor (Peak/RMS) - sensitive to impulses
    crest_factor = crest_factor_shm(X_processed)
    print(f" Crest Factor: {crest_factor.shape}")
    
    # Statistical Moments (mean, std, skewness, kurtosis)
    stat_moments = stat_moments_shm(X_processed)
    print(f" Statistical Moments: {stat_moments.shape}")
    
    # RMS values
    rms_values = rms_shm(X_processed)
    print(f" RMS Values: {rms_values.shape}")
    
    # High-order moment features M6A and M8A
    m6a_features = m6a_shm(X_processed)  # 6th order moment feature
    m8a_features = m8a_shm(X_processed)  # 8th order moment feature
    print(f" M6A Features: {m6a_features.shape}")
    print(f" M8A Features: {m8a_features.shape}")
    
    print("\n Statistical Feature Summary:")
    print(f"Crest Factor - Healthy mean: {np.mean(crest_factor[:n_instances//2, 0]):.3f}")
    print(f"Crest Factor - Damaged mean: {np.mean(crest_factor[n_instances//2:, 0]):.3f}")
    print(f"RMS - Healthy mean: {np.mean(rms_values[:n_instances//2, 0]):.3f}")
    print(f"RMS - Damaged mean: {np.mean(rms_values[n_instances//2:, 0]):.3f}")
    
except Exception as e:
    print(f" Error in statistical feature extraction: {e}")
    raise

4. Advanced Damage Features

Extract specialized gear damage features:

  • NA4M: Normalized 4th moment for residual signals
  • NB4M: Normalized 4th moment for envelope signals

5. Time-Frequency Analysis

Analyze the gear box signals in the time-frequency domain to identify damage-related frequency changes:

  • Continuous Wavelet Transform (CWT) Scalograms
  • Hlder Exponent extraction for nonlinearity detection
  • Discrete Wigner-Ville Distribution (DWVD)
  • Linear Predictive Coding (LPC) Spectrograms
In[6]:
print("Computing time-frequency representations...")

# Select a subset for time-frequency analysis (computationally intensive)
analysis_instances = [0, n_instances//2]  # One healthy, one damaged
channel_idx = 0  # Analyze first channel

try:
    # 1. Continuous Wavelet Transform Scalogram
    print("Computing CWT Scalograms...")
    
    # Parameters for CWT
    f_min = 50   # Minimum frequency (Hz)
    f_max = 2000 # Maximum frequency (Hz) 
    n_scale = 64 # Number of scales
    
    # Compute scalogram for selected instances
    scalograms = []
    hoelder_exponents = []
    
    for i, inst_idx in enumerate(analysis_instances):
        # Extract single signal
        signal = X_processed[:, channel_idx, inst_idx].reshape(-1, 1, 1)
        
        # Compute CWT scalogram
        scalo, f_scalo, t_scalo = cwt_scalogram_shm(
            signal, fs=fs, f_min=f_min, f_max=f_max, n_scale=n_scale
        )
        scalograms.append(scalo[:, :, 0, 0])  # Remove singleton dimensions
        
        # Compute Hlder exponents for nonlinearity detection
        hoelder = hoelder_exp_shm(scalo, f_scalo)
        hoelder_exponents.append(hoelder[:, 0, 0])  # Remove singleton dimensions
        
        condition = "Healthy" if inst_idx < n_instances//2 else "Damaged"
        print(f"   {condition} scalogram: {scalo.shape}")
    
    print(f" CWT Analysis complete")
    
except Exception as e:
    print(f" Error in CWT analysis: {e}")
    scalograms = []
    hoelder_exponents = []

# Plot time-frequency results
if scalograms:
    print("Plotting CWT Scalograms...")
    
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(16, 12))
    
    conditions = ['Healthy', 'Damaged']
    
    for i, (scalo, condition) in enumerate(zip(scalograms, conditions)):

        plot_scalogram_shm(scalo.reshape(n_scale, -1, 1, 1), 
                          channel_index=1, instance=1,

        ax.set_ylabel('Hlder Exponent')

        h_std = np.std(hoelder_exponents[i])

7. Feature Analysis and Comparison

Compare the extracted features between healthy and damaged conditions to assess their diagnostic capability.

In[12]:
# Feature comparison analysis
print("Analyzing feature discrimination capability...")

# Create feature matrix
feature_names = ['Crest Factor', 'RMS', 'Kurtosis', 'M6A', 'M8A', 'NA4M', 'NB4M']

# Extract features for channel 0
features_matrix = np.column_stack([
    crest_factor[:, 0],
    rms_values[:, 0], 
    stat_moments[:, 3],  # Kurtosis (4th column in stat_moments)
    m6a_features[:, 0],
    m8a_features[:, 0],
    na4m_features[:, 0],
    nb4m_features[:, 0]
])

# Split into healthy and damaged
healthy_features = features_matrix[:n_instances//2, :]
damaged_features = features_matrix[n_instances//2:, :]

# Compute statistics
print("\n Feature Statistics:")
print("Feature\t\t\tHealthy MeanStd\t\tDamaged MeanStd\t\tSeparation")
print("-" * 90)

separations = []
for i, name in enumerate(feature_names):
    h_mean, h_std = np.mean(healthy_features[:, i]), np.std(healthy_features[:, i])
    d_mean, d_std = np.mean(damaged_features[:, i]), np.std(damaged_features[:, i])
    
    # Calculate separation (normalized difference)
    separation = abs(d_mean - h_mean) / (h_std + d_std + 1e-10)
    separations.append(separation)
    
    print(f"{name:15s}\t{h_mean:8.3f}{h_std:6.3f}\t\t{d_mean:8.3f}{d_std:6.3f}\t\t{separation:6.3f}")

# Find best features
best_features_idx = np.argsort(separations)[::-1][:3]
print(f"\n Top 3 discriminative features:")
for i, idx in enumerate(best_features_idx):
    print(f"{i+1}. {feature_names[idx]} (separation: {separations[idx]:.3f})")

Analyze the Hlder exponents to quantify signal nonlinearity, which is indicative of gear damage.

In[14]:
# Hlder exponent statistical analysis
if hoelder_exponents:
    print("Analyzing Hlder exponents for nonlinearity detection...")
    
    # Extract statistics from Hlder exponents
    hoelder_stats = []
    conditions = ['Healthy', 'Damaged']
    
    for i, (h_exp, condition) in enumerate(zip(hoelder_exponents, conditions)):
        stats = {
            'mean': np.mean(h_exp),
            'std': np.std(h_exp),
            'min': np.min(h_exp),
            'max': np.max(h_exp),
            'range': np.ptp(h_exp)  # Peak-to-peak
        }
        hoelder_stats.append(stats)
        
        print(f"\n{condition} Gear Box Hlder Statistics:")
        print(f"  Mean: {stats['mean']:.4f}")
        print(f"  Std:  {stats['std']:.4f}")
        print(f"  Range: {stats['range']:.4f}")
    
    # Plot comparison
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 3, figsize=(18, 5))
    
    # Time series comparison
    axes[0].plot(t_scalo, hoelder_exponents[0], 'b-', label='Healthy', linewidth=2)
    axes[0].plot(t_scalo, hoelder_exponents[1], 'r-', label='Damaged', linewidth=2)
    axes[0].set_xlabel('Time (s)')
    axes[0].set_ylabel('Hlder Exponent')
    axes[0].set_title('Hlder Exponent Comparison')
    axes[0].legend()
    axes[0].grid(True)
    
    # Histogram comparison
    axes[1].hist(hoelder_exponents[0], bins=30, alpha=0.7, color='blue', label='Healthy', density=True)
    axes[1].hist(hoelder_exponents[1], bins=30, alpha=0.7, color='red', label='Damaged', density=True)
    axes[1].set_xlabel('Hlder Exponent')
    axes[1].set_ylabel('Density')
    axes[1].set_title('Hlder Exponent Distribution')
    axes[1].legend()
    axes[1].grid(True)
    
    # Box plot comparison
    bp = axes[2].boxplot([hoelder_exponents[0], hoelder_exponents[1]], 
                        labels=['Healthy', 'Damaged'], patch_artist=True)
    bp['boxes'][0].set_facecolor('lightblue')
    bp['boxes'][1].set_facecolor('lightcoral')
    axes[2].set_ylabel('Hlder Exponent')
    axes[2].set_title('Hlder Exponent Statistics')
    axes[2].grid(True)
    
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()
    
    # Nonlinearity assessment
    h_diff = hoelder_stats[1]['mean'] - hoelder_stats[0]['mean']
    print(f"\n Nonlinearity Assessment:")
    print(f"Hlder exponent difference (Damaged - Healthy): {h_diff:.4f}")
    
    if abs(h_diff) > 0.05:
        print(" Significant nonlinearity detected - indicative of damage")
    else:
        print("  Minimal nonlinearity difference detected")
        
    print(" Hlder exponent analysis complete")

10. Technical Implementation Notes

This notebook successfully demonstrates the implementation of Phase 17 of the SHMTools MATLAB-to-Python conversion project.

Implemented Functions:

Statistical Analysis (shmtools.core.statistics):

  • crest_factor_shm() - Peak-to-RMS ratio calculation
  • stat_moments_shm() - First four statistical moments
  • rms_shm() - Root mean square calculation
  • m6a_shm(), m8a_shm() - High-order moment features
  • na4m_shm(), nb4m_shm() - Normalized damage features

Time-Frequency Analysis (shmtools.core.spectral):

  • cwt_scalogram_shm() - Continuous Wavelet Transform with edge mirroring
  • hoelder_exp_shm() - Hlder exponent extraction for nonlinearity detection
  • dwvd_shm() - Discrete Wigner-Ville Distribution
  • lpc_spectrogram_shm() - Linear Predictive Coding spectrograms
  • wavelet_shm() - Wavelet generation functions

Signal Processing (shmtools.core.preprocessing):

  • analytic_signal_shm() - Hilbert transform implementation
  • envelope_shm() - Signal envelope extraction
  • demean_shm() - DC bias removal

Visualization (shmtools.plotting.spectral_plots):

  • plot_time_freq_shm() - Time-frequency visualization
  • plot_scalogram_shm() - CWT scalogram plotting
  • plot_roc_shm() - ROC curve visualization

Key Technical Achievements:

  1. MATLAB Compatibility: All functions maintain exact MATLAB _shm naming convention
  2. Algorithm Fidelity: Implementations follow original MATLAB algorithms precisely
  3. Comprehensive Documentation: Machine-readable docstrings with GUI metadata
  4. Robust Error Handling: Defensive programming with proper edge case management
  5. Performance Optimization: Vectorized operations where possible

Validation Results:

  • All functions execute without errors
  • Feature extraction produces reasonable discrimination between healthy/damaged states
  • Time-frequency analysis reveals expected spectral characteristics
  • Hlder exponents successfully detect signal nonlinearities

This completes the core implementation requirements for Phase 17: CBM Gear Box Analysis, providing a solid foundation for advanced gear box condition monitoring applications.
